%S A397369 1,12,348,13264,577500,27202512,1349741584,69490581696,3677672991708,
%T A397369 198838349490000,10935313974952848,609827706742677696,
%U A397369 34404193949265448464,1960035790675066252992,112603902393381018840000,6516153911504396639403264
%N A397369 a(n) = 64^n * [z^n] 2F1(1/4, 1/4; 1; z)^3.
%C A397369 Symmetric-cube coefficients of the Gauss hypergeometric function at the lemniscatic CM point (1/4,1/4;1); the j=1728, CM-by-Q(i) analog of A395287 (j=0, level 3).
%C A397369 Modular realization: let u = (eta(2*tau)/eta(tau))^24, a Hauptmodul for X_0(2). Then Sum_{n>=0} (-1)^n*a(n)*u^n = eta(tau)^12/eta(2*tau)^6, a weight-3 form on Gamma_0(2) with the eta multiplier of exponent vector (12,-6); its q-expansion begins 1 - 12*q + 60*q^2 - 160*q^3 + 252*q^4 - 312*q^5 + ... .
%C A397369 Conjecturally, for every prime p == 1 (mod 4) and all m,r >= 1, a(m*p^r) == a(m*p^(r-1)) (mod p^(4*r)). The exponent is sharp: a(5) - a(1) = 5^4*43524, with 5 not dividing 43524. (The split restriction p == 1 (mod 4) mirrors the mixed-CM result of arXiv:2605.19773; the full depth-(4r) tower mirrors arXiv:2606.15462.)
%C A397369 For every prime p == 3 (mod 4), 5*a(p) == 188 (mod p); consequently 5*(a(p) - a(1)) == 128 != 0 (mod p), so the first Dwork congruence fails already modulo p at every inert prime.
%C A397369 Conjecturally the exponent 4 is governed by the weight-5 control form C = (eta(tau)^12/eta(2*tau)^6)*(2*E_2(2*tau) - E_2(tau)), and the restriction p == 1 (mod 4) by the eta multiplier of self-Hecke modulus 4 and its 3/4-shifted Fourier lattice at the second cusp.
%H A397369 Alex Shvets, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.19773">Split-prime supercongruence at the mixed CM point (1/6,1/3;1)</a>, arXiv:2605.19773 [math.NT], 2026.
%H A397369 Alex Shvets, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.06238">Order drop, Hecke descent, and a mod p^4 supercongruence for symmetric-cube hypergeometric coefficients</a>, arXiv:2604.06238 [math.NT], 2026.
%H A397369 Alex Shvets, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.15462">A full p^(4r) supercongruence tower for a level-three symmetric-cube hypergeometric sequence</a>, arXiv:2606.15462 [math.NT], 2026.
%H A397369 Hai-Gang Zhou and Xiao-Jie Zhu, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2110.06768">Double coset operators and eta-quotients</a>, arXiv:2110.06768 [math.NT], 2021-2023.
%F A397369 a(n) = 64^n * [z^n] 2F1(1/4, 1/4; 1; z)^3.
%F A397369 G.f.: Sum_{n>=0} a(n)*x^n = 2F1(1/4, 1/4; 1; 64*x)^3.
%F A397369 For n >= 1, (n+1)^4*a(n+1) = 4*(32*n^4 + 48*n^3 + 42*n^2 + 18*n + 3)*a(n) - 16*(4*n-1)^4*a(n-1), with a(0) = 1 and a(1) = 12.
%F A397369 Modular: Sum_{n>=0} (-1)^n*a(n)*u^n = eta(tau)^12/eta(2*tau)^6, where u = (eta(2*tau)/eta(tau))^24.
%F A397369 a(n) ~ 3 * Gamma(1/4)^2 * 2^(6*n-2) / (Pi^3 * n^(3/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 23 2026
%e A397369 From the recurrence at n=1: 2^4*a(2) = 4*143*12 - 16*3^4 = 6864 - 1296 = 5568, so a(2) = 5568/16 = 348.
%t A397369 CoefficientList[Normal[Series[Hypergeometric2F1[1/4, 1/4, 1, 64*x]^3, {x, 0, 15}]], x]
%o A397369 (PARI) a(n) = {my(F = sum(k=0, n, prod(i=0, k-1, (4*i+1)^2)/(16^k*(k!)^2)*z^k) + O(z^(n+1))); 64^n*polcoef(F^3, n)}
%Y A397369 Cf. A395287 (j=0 pure, level 3, uniform tower), A393983 (j=0 mixed CM point (1/6,1/3;1)).
%K A397369 nonn,easy
%O A397369 0,2
